[HealthMap/ProMED-mail map
Punjab Province, Pakistan: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5529749,941

There are 2 vaccines to prevent chicken pox:
MMRV: combined measles, mumps, rubella, and varicella (chickenpox) vaccine
Varicella: varicella (chickenpox) vaccine

Chickenpox vaccine is very effective. 2 doses of the vaccine are about 98 percent effective at preventing chickenpox. Some people who are vaccinated against chickenpox may still get the disease. However, it is usually milder with fewer skin blisters and little or no fever.

Children under 13 years old should get 2 doses of the chickenpox vaccine [initially] at 12 through 15 months, 2nd dose: 4 through 6 years (may be given earlier, if at least 3 months after the 1st dose).

People 13 years or older (who have never had chickenpox and never received chickenpox vaccine) should get 2 doses at least 28 days apart.

MMRV is licensed for use in children 12 months-12 years old. Your child's doctor can help you decide which vaccine to use.

However, pregnant women should wait to get the chickenpox vaccine until after they have given birth. Women should not get pregnant for 1 month after getting the chickenpox vaccine.

(Excerpted from https://www.vaccines.gov/diseases/chickenpox/index.html)

If people are hesitant to have their children vaccinated with MMR vaccine, the same problems with vaccine insufficiency will be encountered with MMRV vaccine. This is the most efficient approach and is highly effective. Whether keeping varicella vaccine as a separate vaccine will be more acceptable to the individuals reluctant to allow the MMR vaccine is a question. - Mod.LK]
